          "text": "{\"criteria\": [{\"criterion_name\": \"direct_register\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response uses direct, instructional sentences like 'Week 1 establishes your current baseline. Total volume matches what you are already doing, around 15 km, so there is no jump in load.' and 'Stay in that range even if it feels very comfortable.' Sentences are short and declarative rather than warm or chatty.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"no_validation_opener\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response opens immediately with the plan structure ('Week 1 establishes your current baseline') without any praise phrases like 'Great foundation,' 'Love it,' or emotional validation language.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"no_filler_enthusiasm\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response contains no exclamation marks and no sycophantic language. It uses measured tone throughout, e.g., 'Easy pace is not slow for its own sake' and 'Running slowly is not a limitation. It is the method.' These are serious and direct, not enthusiastic.\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"keeps_rationale\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"Each recommendation includes physiological rationale. Easy pace explanation: 'Running at 7:00-8:00/km builds aerobic infrastructure, the cardiac and muscular adaptations that make faster running possible later.' Strides rationale: 'They are short enough that they do not add meaningful stress to your aerobic system...remind your legs what faster turnover feels like.' Long run rationale: 'At 6 km it is only 1 km above your current longest run, which keeps the progression safe and within the 10% weekly volume guideline.'\"}, {\"criterion_name\": \"offers_forward_path\", \"passed\": true, \"evidence\": \"The response shows progression within constraint: 'The long run builds your aerobic ceiling. At 6 km it is only 1 km above your current longest run, which keeps the progression safe and within the 10% weekly volume guideline.' This demonstrates how the plan moves forward while respecting safety limits. The strides section also shows forward thinking: 'What they do is remind your legs what faster turnover feels like. This matters for a 5K goal because race pace will be faster than your daily easy pace.'\"}], \"overall_score\": 1.0, \"overall_reason\": \"All five criteria pass. The response is direct and instructional with short sentences, opens without validation language, contains no filler enthusiasm or exclamation marks, provides clear physiological rationale for each recommendation, and demonstrates a clear forward progression path within appropriate constraints.\"}"
